Machine Learning Project¶

Introduction¶

The dataset consists of a large set of data points provided over 64 financial indicators. These financial indicators serve as the feature set for our machine learning problem and consist of numerical data. The eventual goal of the machine learning model is to predict whether the company will go bankrupt or not, therefore, it is a binary classification problem with its prediction values as 1 = Bankrupt and 0 = Not Bankrupt. The project also covers various scenarios one comes accros when dealing with data in the real world such as missing data, haphazard attribute names, irregular attribute values, co-related features and unbalanced classes. We apply various preprocessing methods to address these data issues.

Date 28/Nov/2019.

Data Analysis and Visualization¶

We start by performing data analysis on the dataset. There are 64 feautres and 10503 instances. The label is categorical in nature. Hence, we decide to use classification algorithms for prediction. Here, we observe that the classes are unbalanced. Class corresponding to non-bankruptcy has 10008 instances and class corresponding to bankruptcy has 495 instances. The same is shown by Pie Chart.

As the first step, we import all the required libraries followed by the data from the CSV files into the Jupyter notebook. In the next step, we use the replace method to deal with irregular label values such as b'0 and b'1. We then proceed with Data Visualization. We have plotted the Pair Plot.

To get a glance at the data we plotted some points, however we could not do it over all the features so we show only the first 10 features.

Data Preprocessing¶

For several reasons, real world data sets contain missing values, unbalanced classes, etc. However to estimate a model it is necessary that our dataset, which may contain non-numerical values, is expresed only with numerical values. There are several strategies we can us to fill these missing values. We use the function SimpleImputer to fill the missing data values with the average. [1]

In [17]:
imp = SimpleImputer(missing_values=np.nan, strategy='most_frequent')
imp.fit(X)
X = imp.transform(X)

from sklearn.svm import LinearSVC
from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectFromModel

print("Original feature size")
print("X.shape", X.shape)

lsvc = LinearSVC(penalty="l1", dual=False, C=0.1, max_iter=1000000).fit(X, y)
model = SelectFromModel(lsvc, prefit=True)
X = model.transform(X) # select only new features 
print("Feature size after regularization")
print("X.shape", X.shape)

With L1 or Lasso regularatizations, many of the coeffiecients are zero. Since our goal is to reduce the dimensionality of the data, this method can be used along with feature selection. In particular, sparse estimators useful for this purpose are Linear Model Lasso for regression, and Support Vector Classifier for classification. [2]

Hyperparameters Tuning¶

In this section, the Hyperparameters are tuned for the 10 models that are picked. The most relevant and commonly specified Hyperparameters values are chosen and plugged in the models in order to achieve good predicitions. The scikit-learn library example [3] was referred for selecting the parameters for each model.

In Logistic Regression the hyperparameters are tuned using 3 different techniques- LASSO regularisation, Ridge regularisation and Elastic net. It is specified in the penalty parameter by 'l1', 'l2' or 'elasticnet'. The other parameters are set as 0.1 for tolerance for stopping criteria (tol), 0.5 for inverse of regularization strength (C) and the solver is set as 'saga' which is the algorithm to use in the optimization problem. The number of neighbors selected for KNeighbors Classifier is 3. In Support Vector Classification model the kernel type is specified as "liner" for SVM, the penalty parameter C of the error term is set to 0.025 and probability estimates are enabled. For SVM with RBF kernel, the kernel coefficient is given as the parameter along with penalty parameter and probablity. In the Decision Tree Classifier the maximum depth of the tree is given as the parameter and set to 5. For AdaBoost, the L2 penalty (regularization term) parameter alpha is set to 1 and maximum number of iterations are given as 1000.

Training models and Comparing Metrics¶

We split the model into train set and test set. We take 80% of the instances to train the model and keep the remaining 20% to test it. We are training and testing on 10 different classifiers namely Logistic Regression with Lasso, Logistic Regression with Ridge, Logistic Regression with Elastic Net, KNeighbors Classifier, Linear SVM, RBF SVM, Decision Tree, Neural Net, AdaBoost and Naive Bayes, in order to select the best fit for the dataset. After training and testing, ROC AUC and F1 score are calculated. Based on these metrics we choose the best model for the given dataset.

When we have unbalanced classes, we would only have a high presicion value by predicting the mayority class. There are several strategies to handle unbalanced classes. One is penalizing the model when it predicts incorrectly in the minority class. This was done by adding class_weight='balanced'. One other aproach is resampling the minority class so it is balanced, or downsampling the mayority class. After we chose to resample the minority class, some models stop predicting only the mayority class. [4]

In [20]:
scores = []

#data split
# Separate majority and minority classes
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.20, random_state=0)

y_train = y_train.reshape(len(y_train),1)
data = np.concatenate((X_train, y_train), axis=1)
df_minority = data[data[:,-1] == 1]
df_mayority = data[data[:,-1] == 0]

print("mayority class size", df_mayority.size)
print("minority class size", df_minority.size)

df_minority_upsampled = resample(df_minority, 
                                 replace=True,     # sample with replacement
                                 n_samples=np.shape(df_mayority)[0],    # to match majority class
                                 random_state=123) # reproducible results

print("upsample size", df_minority_upsampled.shape)
print("X_train original size", X_train.shape)
X_train = np.concatenate((df_mayority[:,0:-1], df_minority_upsampled[:,0:-1]))
y_train = np.concatenate((df_mayority[:, -1], df_minority_upsampled[:,-1]))

print("x train size", X_train.shape)
print("y_train_size", y_train.shape)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 8))
for name, clf in zip(names, classifiers):
    print("Training " , name + '...')
    model = make_pipeline(
        StandardScaler(),
        clf).fit(X_train, y_train)
    fprs, tprs, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1])
    roc_score = round(roc_auc_score(y_test, model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]),4)
    ax.plot(fprs, tprs, label=name + " " + str(roc_score))
    ax.set_xlabel('False positive rate')
    ax.set_ylabel('True positive rate')
    ax.set_title(r"All models with thresholds $0, 0.05, 0.1, \ldots, 0.95, 1.0$");
    ax.legend()
    print(name + " ROC_AUC_SCORE :", roc_score)
    print("F1 score: ", round(f1_score(y_test, model.predict(X_test)),4)) 
    print("Recall: ", round(recall_score(y_test, model.predict(X_test)),4)) 
    print("Precision: ", round(precision_score(y_test, model.predict(X_test)),4)) 
    print("------------------------------------------------------")

Model Selection¶

From above, we can see that most of the models have a good F1 score. However, the models with the top ROC-AUC score are AdaBoost and Random Forest. To decide the best between them, we perform K-Fold Cross Validation on these two models. In k-fold cross valdidation we take k = 10. We calculate both F1 score and ROC-AUC using the command cross_val_score. We chose the final model based only on the F1 score as our data is unbalanced.

In [ ]:
names = ["Decision Tree", "AdaBoost"]

classifiers = [
    DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=5),
    AdaBoostClassifier()]

scores = ['f1' , 'roc_auc', 'f1_micro']

#data split

from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold

kfold = KFold(n_splits = 10, shuffle = True, random_state = 3)
for name, clf in zip(names, classifiers):
    print("Training " , name + '...')
    for score in scores:
        Model_scores = cross_val_score(clf, X_train, y_train, scoring = score, cv = kfold)
        avg = round(np.mean(Model_scores),4)
        print("Scores: ", score , avg)
    print('----------------------------------------------------')

Conclusion¶

In this project, we learned how to clean a real-life data set, apply classification modelling techniques and evaluate their performance. The first step to any Machine Learning project is to clean, correct and input any missing values of a particular datapoint. We perform feature selection and select 35 features. As such, almost half the features are not related to the final goal and are weak features - our dataset is noisy. Noise has a negative effect on the predictive performance of the machine learning model and also increases the training time. We chose ten broad classification models to get a rough idea of our final model. Referring to the scikit library, we selected parameters for each model was done. Based on the results of ROC and F1 scores we finetuned our selection of the classification to two models viz. Adaboost and Decision Tree. K-Fold cross validation, being fast and a classification method showing low bias, was preferred. The two final models were compared again and the ROC and F-1 scores of the same were found out. Based on these scores. we conclude that AdaBoost is the best model.

AdaBoost:¶

F1 Score: 0.20

ROC Score: 0.81

Our model has a precision score of 12% to predict whether a company will go bankrupt or not. While this may not be a high value, it is representative of real-world situations, which is better than having an unnaturally high precision value by just predicting the majority class and ignoring the minority class.
